---

<TutorialLayout title="Claude Code Fundamentals" description="Learn the basics of Claude Code: setup, commands, and your first AI-assisted coding session.">

	<!-- Section 1: What is Claude Code -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">What is Claude Code?</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Claude Code is an agentic coding tool that lives in your terminal. Unlike chat-based AI assistants where you copy-paste code back and forth, Claude Code reads your files, runs commands, edits code, and commits changes — all within your project directory.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Think of it as a pair programmer who can actually touch the keyboard. You describe what you want, and Claude Code figures out which files to read, what changes to make, and how to verify the result. It sees your entire project — not just the snippet you pasted.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			In this tutorial, you'll install Claude Code, learn the core commands, and build a task tracker CLI from scratch using nothing but natural language prompts. By the end, you'll have a working project and a feel for how AI-assisted development actually works in practice.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 2: Installation & Setup -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Installation & Setup</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Claude Code is installed with a one-line command. Run the appropriate command for your platform:
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3">macOS / Linux / Windows (WSL)</h3>
		<pre class="bg-surface-alt rounded-lg p-4 mb-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm text-text">curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.sh | bash</code></pre>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3">Windows (PowerShell)</h3>
		<pre class="bg-surface-alt rounded-lg p-4 mb-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm text-text">irm https://claude.ai/install.ps1 | iex</code></pre>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3">Windows (CMD)</h3>
		<pre class="bg-surface-alt rounded-lg p-4 mb-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm text-text">curl -fsSL https://claude.ai/install.cmd -o install.cmd && install.cmd && del install.cmd</code></pre>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Verify the installation:
		</p>
		<pre class="bg-surface-alt rounded-lg p-4 mb-4 overflow-x-auto"><code class="text-sm text-text">claude --version</code></pre>

		<div class="bg-surface-alt border border-border rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
			<p class="text-text text-sm">
				<strong class="text-accent">Windows note:</strong> Native Windows installs require <a href="https://git-scm.com/downloads/win" class="text-accent hover:underline">Git for Windows</a>. I highly recommend you install Claude Code inside <strong>WSL</strong> (Windows Subsystem for Linux) using the macOS/Linux command above — WSL does not require Git for Windows. If you're unsure which to pick: use WSL if you prefer Linux toolchains, or native Windows if your projects use Windows-native tools.
			</p>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			On first launch, Claude Code will ask you to authenticate with your Anthropic account. Follow the browser prompt to connect your API key. You'll need a Pro, Max, Team, or Enterprise plan — the free Claude.ai plan does not include Claude Code access.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Now create a project directory. Claude Code works best when launched from the root of a project — it uses the directory structure and any existing files to understand context.
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Create your project"
			python={`# Create a new project directory
mkdir task-tracker && cd task-tracker

# Initialize a Python project
python -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate  # On Windows: venv\\Scripts\\activate
pip install click         # We'll use Click for the CLI

# Start Claude Code
claude`}
			typescript={`# Create a new project directory
