	<!-- Section 4: Core Commands -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Core Commands</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Claude Code responds to natural language, but there are a few built-in slash commands worth knowing. These control Claude Code's behavior rather than asking it to write code.
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-1">/help</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Show available commands and usage tips.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-1">/clear</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Reset the conversation context. Useful when you want to start a new task without prior context influencing the response.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-1">/compact</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Compress the conversation to free up context window space. Claude Code summarizes what happened so far and continues with a shorter context.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-1">/cost</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">Show how much the current session has cost in API usage.</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-accent font-mono text-sm mb-1">/config</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm">View and modify settings — model selection, permissions, and behavior preferences.</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The most important thing to understand: you rarely need slash commands. Claude Code is designed for natural language. Instead of memorizing commands, just describe what you want.
		</p>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Need to see what changed? Ask "what files did you just modify?" Want to undo something? Say "revert the last change." Want to understand existing code? Point at it: "explain what the <code class="text-accent">load_tasks</code> function does."
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 5: Writing Effective Prompts -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Writing Effective Prompts</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			The quality of Claude Code's output depends heavily on how you ask. Here are the patterns that work.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3 mt-8">Be specific about behavior, not implementation</h3>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Don't tell Claude Code <em>how</em> to write the code. Tell it <em>what the code should do</em>. It knows the idioms for your language.
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-red-400 text-sm mb-1">Weak prompt:</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm font-mono">"Create a function that uses a for loop to iterate over the tasks array and filter out done ones"</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-green-400 text-sm mb-1">Better prompt:</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm font-mono">"Add a command that shows only incomplete tasks"</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3 mt-8">Give context about why</h3>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Claude Code makes better decisions when it understands the motivation, not just the ask.
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-red-400 text-sm mb-1">Weak prompt:</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm font-mono">"Add timestamps to tasks"</p>
			</div>
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-green-400 text-sm mb-1">Better prompt:</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm font-mono">"Add created_at and completed_at timestamps to tasks. I want to be able to see how long tasks take to finish."</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3 mt-8">Point at specific files</h3>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			When your project grows, be explicit about where you want changes.
		</p>

		<div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
			<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-4">
				<p class="text-green-400 text-sm mb-1">Good prompt:</p>
				<p class="text-text-muted text-sm font-mono">"In task_tracker.py, add a 'remove' command that deletes a task by ID"</p>
			</div>
		</div>

		<h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-heading mb-3 mt-8">Iterate, don't restart</h3>
		<p class="text-text mb-6">
			Claude Code remembers the full conversation. If the first result isn't quite right, refine it: "That's close, but make the output more compact — one task per line, no extra spacing." This is faster than re-explaining from scratch.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- Section 6: Extending the Task Tracker -->
	<section class="mb-16">
		<h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-heading mb-4">Extending the Task Tracker</h2>
		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Now that you have a working CLI, let's use Claude Code to add a feature — timestamps on tasks. This is how real AI-assisted development feels: incremental, conversational, building on what's already there.
		</p>

		<div class="rounded-lg border border-border bg-surface p-6 mb-6">
			<p class="text-text-muted text-sm mb-2">Your prompt:</p>
			<p class="text-text font-mono text-sm">
				Add created_at and completed_at timestamps to tasks. When I list tasks, show how long ago each task was created. When a task is marked done, record when it was completed.
			</p>
		</div>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
			Claude Code will read the existing code, understand the task structure, and modify both the data model and the display logic:
		</p>

		<CodeGroup
			title="Updated task model with timestamps"
			python={`import json
import sys
from datetime import datetime, timezone
from pathlib import Path

import click

TASKS_FILE = Path("tasks.json")


def load_tasks() -> list[dict]:
    if TASKS_FILE.exists():
        return json.loads(TASKS_FILE.read_text())
    return []


def save_tasks(tasks: list[dict]) -> None:
    TASKS_FILE.write_text(json.dumps(tasks, indent=2))


def time_ago(iso_str: str) -> str:
    dt = datetime.fromisoformat(iso_str)
    delta = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - dt
    if delta.days > 0:
        return f"{delta.days}d ago"
    hours = delta.seconds // 3600
    if hours > 0:
        return f"{hours}h ago"
    minutes = delta.seconds // 60
    return f"{minutes}m ago"


@click.group()
def cli():
    """A simple task tracker."""
    pass


@cli.command()
@click.argument("title")
def add(title: str):
    """Add a new task."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    task = {
        "id": len(tasks) + 1,
        "title": title,
        "done": False,
        "created_at": datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(),
        "completed_at": None,
    }
    tasks.append(task)
    save_tasks(tasks)
    click.echo(f"Added task {task['id']}: {title}")


@cli.command(name="list")
def list_tasks():
    """List all tasks."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    if not tasks:
        click.echo("No tasks yet. Add one with: task-tracker add 'My task'")
        return
    for task in tasks:
        status = "x" if task["done"] else " "
        age = time_ago(task["created_at"])
        click.echo(f"[{status}] {task['id']}: {task['title']}  ({age})")


@cli.command()
@click.argument("task_id", type=int)
def done(task_id: int):
    """Mark a task as complete."""
    tasks = load_tasks()
    for task in tasks:
        if task["id"] == task_id:
            task["done"] = True
            task["completed_at"] = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()
            save_tasks(tasks)
            click.echo(f"Completed: {task['title']}")
            return
    click.echo(f"Task {task_id} not found.", err=True)
    sys.exit(1)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    cli()`}
			typescript={`import { Command } from "commander";
import { readFileSync, writeFileSync, existsSync } from "fs";

const TASKS_FILE = "tasks.json";

interface Task {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  done: boolean;
  createdAt: string;
  completedAt: string | null;
}

function loadTasks(): Task[] {
  if (existsSync(TASKS_FILE)) {
    return JSON.parse(readFileSync(TASKS_FILE, "utf-8"));
  }
  return [];
}

function saveTasks(tasks: Task[]): void {
  writeFileSync(TASKS_FILE, JSON.stringify(tasks, null, 2));
}

function timeAgo(isoStr: string): string {
  const delta = Date.now() - new Date(isoStr).getTime();
  const days = Math.floor(delta / 86_400_000);
  if (days > 0) return \`\${days}d ago\`;
  const hours = Math.floor(delta / 3_600_000);
  if (hours > 0) return \`\${hours}h ago\`;
  const minutes = Math.floor(delta / 60_000);
  return \`\${minutes}m ago\`;
}

const program = new Command();
program.name("task-tracker").description("A simple task tracker.");

program
  .command("add <title>")
  .description("Add a new task")
  .action((title: string) => {
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    const task: Task = {
      id: tasks.length + 1,
      title,
      done: false,
      createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
      completedAt: null,
    };
    tasks.push(task);
    saveTasks(tasks);
    console.log(\`Added task \${task.id}: \${title}\`);
  });

program
  .command("list")
  .description("List all tasks")
  .action(() => {
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    if (tasks.length === 0) {
      console.log("No tasks yet. Add one with: task-tracker add 'My task'");
      return;
    }
    for (const task of tasks) {
      const status = task.done ? "x" : " ";
      const age = timeAgo(task.createdAt);
      console.log(\`[\${status}] \${task.id}: \${task.title}  (\${age})\`);
    }
  });

program
  .command("done <taskId>")
  .description("Mark a task as complete")
  .action((taskId: string) => {
    const tasks = loadTasks();
    const task = tasks.find((t) => t.id === parseInt(taskId));
    if (!task) {
      console.error(\`Task \${taskId} not found.\`);
      process.exit(1);
    }
    task.done = true;
    task.completedAt = new Date().toISOString();
    saveTasks(tasks);
    console.log(\`Completed: \${task.title}\`);
  });

program.parse();`}
		/>

		<p class="text-text mb-4">
